	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Farmers face more barriers in Africa than elsewhere  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 April 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In a World Bank report on how Africa can increase its own food production, published in October 2012, the Bank’s Vice-President for Africa, Makhtar Diop, argues that “farmers in Africa face more barriers in accessing the inputs they need and in getting their food to consumers in African cities, than do suppliers from the rest of the world.” Noting that Africa has increasingly met its rising food demand from extra-regional imports, the report argues that “business as usual with food staples is not sustainable”, given that global food prices are rising and that population growth, combined with changing demand patterns, “will double demands over the next 10 years”.</p><p>Complaining that the idea of food security “has too often been twisted by narrow nationalistic visions”, the report argues that if Africa is to make itself food secure, it must be easier for farmers to trade regionally across borders. But moving food across borders from surplus to deficit areas involves a set of steps, at each of which “the extent of competition and the nature of government policies can influence the price the consumer pays (and its variability), as well as the price that the farmer receives for the product.”</p><p>The report examines trade and competition barriers affecting five points in regional value chains:</p>
<ul>

<li>inputs (with trade barriers denying African farmers higher-yielding seeds and better fertilisers); </li>

<li>transport (which is often costly – up to 10 times higher than in the OECD for short distances); </li>

<li>trade policies (which can be opaque and ”volatile” – in some instances small groups of officials decide on export bans “via unpublished decisions and purely internal consultations”); </li>

<li>crossing borders (which is “costly and dangerous”); and </li>

<li>distribution services (which can be inefficient).</li>

</ul>
<p>The report considers that shortcomings in these areas serve to fragment regional markets and discourage the investments (both smallholder and large scale) by the private sector that are required to fulfil Africa’s agricultural potential.</p><p>In January, the African Union announced that an action plan to accelerate intra-African trade has been adopted. “The plan to&nbsp;help implement the Continental Free Trade Area (CFTA) by 2017” was laid out during the Second Africa Trade Forum held in September 2012 in Ethiopia. It has been reported that the Trade Observatory and African Business Council agreed in the plan have already been established.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank ‘Africa can help feed Africa: Removing barriers to regional trade in food staples’, Washington, October 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRICA/Resources/Africa-Can-Feed-Africa-" target="_self">http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTAFRICA/Resources/Africa-Can-Feed-A...</a>Report.pdf</p><p><i>Ghana Business News</i>, ‘Action plan adopted to push key policy on intra-African trade’, 25 January 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2013/01/25/action-plan-adopted-to-push-key-policy-on-intra-african-trade/ " target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2013/01/25/action-plan-adopted-to-push-key-policy-...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Expanding production within regional value chains commonly requires concerted action at many levels to build commercially sustainable trade. Even where the policy framework is supportive of production, and physical infrastructure constraints are being addressed, problems of implementation, infrastructure bottlenecks, policy inconsistencies and policy volatility can seriously inhibit the intra-regional flow of food products from surplus to deficit areas.</p><p>Hardly a month passes by without another example of the problems that farmers and traders face in moving food across borders. For example, in February 2013, Zambian sugar exports were denied entry to the Kenyan market on rules of origin grounds, despite the existence of sugar shortages in Kenya, and the Zambian exporter insisting that the sugar was fully compliant with COMESA trade requirements. This dispute rapidly escalated, with Zambia imposing retaliatory duties on Kenyan goods (both food and non-food items), utilising provisions related to trade disputes under the COMESA trade protocol.</p><p>At the policy level therefore, the conclusion of trade agreements is just a starting point. Building efficient systems for the traceability of food products and forensic investigation of trade flows where concerns arise, alongside rapidly activated dispute settlement procedures, is also necessary. This potentially constitutes an important area for increased intra-regional cooperation and ‘aid for trade’ support.</p><p>If government trade policy constraints on the development of intra-regional value chains can be addressed more effectively, this may encourage more private sector investment in order to get to grips with the production- and distribution-related constraints on increasing region-wide food security.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
